// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
//	Created by fenix in 2023
//	License Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License.
//
//  Stare at the black cross and remember: there are no green dots in this image!
//
//  Inspired by:
//
//      https://www.reddit.com/r/OpticalIllusionGifs/comments/3a2x7c/stare_at_the_center_dot_to_see_some_green/
//
//  If you're staring at the cross intently enough, the ring of pink dots will fade
//  away, and a single rotating green dot will be left behind. This illusion is pretty
//  easy to explain. It's based on the "afterimage" idea like those inverted color flags
//  and whatnot:
//
//      hhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afterimage
//
//  The pink dots "antagonize" or "tire out" the red and blue receptors in your retina,
//  leaving a green afterimage. In this animated example, as long as you stare steadily
//  at the cross, the green dots mostly just cancel out the pink ones, except for the one
//  moving missing one, where we see the green. With the movement disabled, the pink
//  dots still disappear; the disappearing one just give us a chance to see the negative
//  afterimage.
//
//  The title of the shader means "This is not a green dot" and is a reference to the
//  1929 painting "The Treachery of Images" by Ren√© Magritte. Which seems like a good
//  title to inspire the title of an optical illusion shader...while I also admit that
//  my usage is far more literal and less meta than the original. I'm not a French 
//  speaker so please correct me if this is not right: I just used Google Translate.
//
//  I feel pretty good about the code golfing on this one, but I probably missed something
//  and submissions in the comments are encouraged.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

// Original by me: 279 chars
//*
void mainImage(out vec4 O, vec2 U)
{
    vec2 R = iResolution.xy,
         u = (U - .5 * R) / R.y,
         v = abs(u) / .01,                       // used to draw cross
         a = atan(u.y, u.x) / 3.14 + vec2(1.06), // normalized angle
         i = a - mod(a, .125);                   // angle index

    i.y -= .5; // generate sin in y component

    O = vec4(v.x < 3. && v.y < .4 || v.y < 3. && v.x < .4 ? 0. : .7) + // draw cross
            4.3 * vec4(1, -1, 1, 1) *                                  // dot color
            max(0., .06                                                // size of dot
                 - length(u + cos(i * 3.14) * .4)                      // distance to nearest dot
                 - max(0., .2 - abs(mod(iTime * 2. + i.x, 2.))));      // turn off a rotating dot
}
/**/
